Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to regulate the banking system adequately, thereby setting the stage for the worst economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current Federal Reserve chairman Jerome Powell should be reconfirmed in office.
It would be a demonstration of bipartisan support.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed to guide us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I heard 25 years ago, when I was chair of President Bill Clinton's economic advisory staff and the confirmation of Greenspan was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid a heavy price for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied him a second term after Volcker had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed Volcker a lot, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
Economic policy requires careful assessment and sensitivity to conflicting objectives.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and characterized by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the United States held clearly different, but well-articulated positions on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell for the populist frenzy).
In my view, Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, only in times of tight labor markets are marginalized groups integrated into the economy and wage gaps reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a trial for every US Federal Reserve chairman.
Already now, the US is facing difficult decisions on what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially a minor problem caused by an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate among African Americans, who have not yet regained their pre-pandemic levels?
Would interest rate hikes (and accordingly an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities with asset-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of a stronger and more pervasive mispricing related to climate change assets.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and risked the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers around the world have already declared this to be the central issue of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues do not belong to the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record in this area suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such a laxity is the last thing the economy currently needs.
An obvious lack of competition and the absence of sufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant actors more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
Yet every student in their second year would have known that you must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argued, Powell does not feel particularly strongly committed to full employment.
On the contrary, Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board regarding the tightening of monetary policy over the past decade has been marked by a series of misjudgments that date back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the Fed's concern, it is a fact that the Bank's policies have important distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early rate hike can stifle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal over stock trading by senior Fed officials has undermined trust in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long been a concern of mine.
After four years of Trump weakened trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock trades would appear inappropriate.
The Fed is somewhat similar to the US Supreme Court.
This is supposed to be above politics, but by the time of Bush v. Gore, we knew that was not the case.
Trump made this clear for all who still had doubts.
Even the Fed is supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is not the case either, by following their party's deregulation agenda.
Yet while the Federal Reserve Board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power has traditionally concentrated in the hands of the Fed chair – much more strongly than with the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the Fed chair who decides what comes up for discussion and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just one example where it is extremely important who sits at the head of the table.
The US needs a Fed that really commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Those who believe that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lack insight.
We do not need an ideologue like Greenspan or a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
We need someone who has deep understanding of economics and who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are certainly a lot of people who meet these conditions.
But Biden does not need to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated his abilities.
Lael Brainard is already sitting on the Federal Open Market Committee, where she has shown her competence and won the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a Federal Reserve chair who maintains continuity and does not disturb the markets, but who also shares his economic and social program.
